==English==
===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/trəʊl/, /trɒl/}}

===Etymology 1===
From Swedish [[troll#Swedish|troll]], from Old Norse [[troll#Old Norse|troll]], of unknown origin.  Compare Swedish [[trolla]], Danish [[trylle]] ‘perform magical arts’.

====Noun====
{{en-noun-reg}}
{{wikipedia}}
# A supernatural being, now especially a grotesque humanoid creature inhabiting caves, hills, or under bridges
# ''(slang)'' An ugly person of either sex.
# A system operator that trolls the Wiktionary looking for articles and user pages with which they disagree. 

=====Translations=====
'''supernatural being'''
{{top}}
*Finnish: [[peikko]]
{{mid}}
*Swedish: troll ''n''
{{bottom}}

===Etymology 2===
Origin uncertain; compare Old French [[troller]] ‘quest, wander’ (modern French [[trôler]]), Middle High German [[trollen]] ‘stroll’.

====Verb====
{{en-infl-reg-consonant|troll||}}
# To [[saunter]], especially to [[cruise]] for a sexual partner
#:''I am '''trolling''' for custom, said the actress to the Bishop.''
# To [[entice]] fish with bait; to [[fish]] using a line and bait.
# by extension, to search (for), to draw out, to entice

====Noun====
{{en-noun-reg}}
# an instance of trolling, especially, in fishing, the [[trail]]ing of a baited line.
# (''Internet'') A [[posting]] to a [[newsgroup]], [[bulletin board]], etc, that is deliberately intended to [[anger]] other [[poster]]s and draw [[argument]]s.

====Translations====
'''posting to a newsgroup'''
{{top}}
*Finnish: [[trolli]], [[trollaus]]
{{mid}}
{{bottom}}


